## Correctness
The implementation satisfies the spec for discovery behavior: it parses `tailscale status --json`, iterates online peers, probes `http://{ip}:8443/federation/v1/identity`, validates identity payload shape, and returns `PeerInfo` for valid peers. Registry persistence is implemented at `~/.promptclaw/federation/peers.json` with requested fields and merge semantics (online updates + offline carry-forward). `tests/test_federation_discovery.py` includes coverage for happy path, missing tailscale, no promptclaw peers, malformed identity, self-IP exclusion, persistence, and merge behavior.

## Completeness
Core acceptance criteria are covered by unit tests and implementation. One gap is lifecycle wiring: this change introduces discovery and registry utilities but does not show an orchestrator/scheduler call site that periodically invokes discovery and writes the merged registry, so end-to-end federation behavior is only partially exercised by tests.

## Consistency
Code organization and naming are consistent with existing patterns (`promptclaw/federation/` package, stdlib-only per spec, small focused module + tests). Tests follow existing mocking style used in the suite. No major style violations observed in touched files.

## Security
No credentials are logged or embedded. Request/response handling is local-trust based and uses plain HTTP, which aligns with the documented task assumptions but should be considered a temporary trust boundary decision (also recorded in escalations). Exception handling avoids leaking stack traces.

## Quality
Overall quality is good: focused implementation, deterministic tests, and explicit helper boundaries (`discover`, `_probe`, persistence/merge). Error handling avoids hard failures in absent/unresponsive Tailscale environments.

## Issues Found
- [ ] **Minor:** No scheduled or consumer integration was added to invoke `discover_peers()` and persist merged results automatically; only utility functions are now present.

## Verdict: PASS WITH NOTES

